    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. i think the issue is i'm using a while loop with a counter that increments at the end of the block, so it checks the condition, runs the code, then increments, which makes it hit the loop one extra time when i don't want it to. if i change it to a for loop with range() like you suggested, does that usually solve it?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, switching to a `for` loop with `range()` often solves this because the iteration count is strictly defined before the loop starts, eliminating manual counter management entirely. Inside a `range()`, the loop variable will never equal the stop value, ensuring exactly the intended number of passes without risking an early or late termination. This approach pushes the logic for the iteration count out of the condition check and into the loop generation, which is the most reliable way to prevent off-by-one errors.",
      "source": "target",
